{#- One blueprint serves both functions: func_type selects "tg" or "ctg".
    freq is the inner coefficient k in tg(k*x)/ctg(k*x). Pick the human name and
    the LaTeX command accordingly; render the argument as x or k*x. -#}
{%- set name = 'тангенса' if func_type == 'tg' else 'котангенса' -%}
{%- set latex = '\\tan' if func_type == 'tg' else '\\cot' -%}
{%- set innerLatex = 'x' if freq == 1 else (freq ~ 'x') -%}
PROBLEM TO POSE (turn ONLY this into the word problem; keep every number exactly as written):
- Function: y = {{ func_type }}({{ innerLatex }})
- Ask the student to state the properties of this {{ name }} function from its graph — its
  domain (the punctured points / ОДЗ where the function does not exist), its range,
  parity (even/odd), and period.

=== INTERNAL (guidance for you only — never show, restate, paraphrase, number, or hint any of this to the student) ===
- Key facts to recall: the graph has vertical asymptotes at the points where the function
  is undefined and repeats with a SHORTER period than sine and cosine; a coefficient k
  inside compresses the graph, dividing the period and the spacing of the punctured points
  by k. It is unbounded along OY and symmetric about the origin.
- Render all math as LaTeX inside $...$ (e.g. $y = {{ latex }}\left({{ innerLatex }}\right)$).
- Do NOT state or hint at the answer: the punctured points / domain, range, parity, or
  period of the function must NOT be given to the student.
